    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT95-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ pāṅkaṟku uraittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Declared to the companion by HIM.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT95">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                mālvarai yiḻitarun tūveḷ ḷaruvi</l>
<l>                kaṉmukait tatumpum paṉmalarc cāraṟ</l>
<l>                ciṟukuṭik kuṟavaṉ peruntōṭ kuṟumaka</l>
<l>                ṇīrō raṉṉa cāya</l>
<l>                ṟīyō raṉṉaveṉ ṉuraṉavit taṉṟē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <l>The big-shouldered little daughter of the hill habitant</l>
            <l rend="indent4">from the small hamlet<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṟukuṭi</term> is explained as a nomen proprium by TVG, but with a designation as frequent and formulaic as this such an interpretation sounds quite baroque, unless the context supplies some hint.</note></l>
            <l rend="indent">on the slope with many blossoms, where in stone caves</l>
            <l rend="indent">the pure white waterfall resounds,</l>
            <l rend="indent3">plunging down from the big mountain,</l>
            <l>[her] grace, just like water, got</l>
            <l>my strength, just like fire, extinguished.</l>

            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
